# A bare untyped `x := Ok(v)` / `x := Err(v)` fixes only ONE of Result's two type
# params; the other is never inferred from a later use (unlike None, which can be
# grounded), so it must be annotated. Both compilers reject. tychoc0 used to accept
# it and store a partial `Result(int,)` type that a downstream match then mis-handled.
fn main():
    x := Ok(1)
    print("x")
